Make YCSB's postgrenosql binding thread-safe (one connection per client thread).

Upstream YCSB (all versions through 0.17.0) declares the JDBC connection and the
prepared-statement cache as *static* in PostgreNoSQLDBClient:

    private static ConcurrentMap<StatementType, PreparedStatement> cachedStatements;
    private static Connection connection;

YCSB hands every client thread its own DB instance, but `static` defeats that: all
threads end up sharing ONE Connection and ONE PreparedStatement per statement type.
init() compounds it by returning early for every thread after the first. The
operation methods then do, with no synchronization:

    insertStatement.setObject(2, object);
    insertStatement.setString(1, key);
    insertStatement.executeUpdate();

With threadcount > 1 the threads interleave parameter writes on that shared
statement and corrupt the JDBC protocol stream. Measured against postgres:18.4 with
KV-Bench's threadcount=8 (recordcount=1000): 0 of 1000 rows loaded, failing with
"invalid message format", "duplicate key value violates unique constraint" (one
thread's key overwritten by another before execute) and "This connection has been
closed". With threadcount=1 the same load inserts 1000/1000. Reproduces identically
on postgres 16, 17 and 18, so it is the binding and not the server.

This matters beyond a crash: YCSB still prints [OVERALL] when every operation
errors, so a totally failed load looks like a successful one. The run phases then
measure error paths against an empty table -- and the per-op LOG.error calls emit
~170 bytes each, which is what pushed a full run's logs past Postgres's 256 MB
jsonb ceiling in GMT.

The fix drops `static` from the three fields so each thread's DB instance opens and
owns its own connection, and removes the early-return so every instance actually
initialises. cleanup() becomes per-instance (closing each thread's connection)
rather than only acting on the last thread, which would otherwise leak 7 of 8.

One behavioural change beyond thread-safety: init() now rethrows as DBException
instead of only logging. Upstream swallows a failed connect, leaving connection ==
null so every subsequent op NPEs into the same log flood. Failing loudly at startup
is the point of this exercise. Drop that one hunk line if you want a strictly
minimal diff.

Applies to: YCSB 0.17.0
